He was born on January 5, 1942, the youngest of 6 children to the late Ernest John Rogers and Hallie Goad Rogers of Hollow Springs, Cannon County, TN. After graduating from Woodbury Central High School in 1960 where he served as President of the Student Body, he was accepted into West Point Military Academy, however, he decided to attend local college where he could be closer to his family. After college, he worked at Sperry Rand Corporation in Florida, Wright Industries of Nashville and AEDC as a master machinist. In March of 1972, he started his own business, Universal Machining Company, which he later incorporated as Universal Technologies, Inc. and still remains in Estill Springs. As a visionary person and CEO/President of Universal Technologies, Inc., he excelled in "doing things no one else could do". With his talent and determination, he forged key components for the US defense systems. He developed products and processes that have resulted in significant savings to the US military. For recognition of these efforts, he was named Tennessee Small Business Man of the Year in 1989. Privately he would say, "I guess God blessed me with the mechanical talent that in my mind I could see a project finished before it had begun." Mr. Rogers also enjoyed participation in the Tennessee Walking Horse Community as he personally owned a number of beautiful walking horses which he cherished. He was a private man who had many friends. Mr. Rogers was a Christian, he was very spiritual, and he loved his Lord dearly. He treated his employees with fairness, kindness, love and respect. He will be missed by all that had the privilege to know him. In addition to his parents, Mr. Rogers was preceded in death by his brother, Mitchell Rogers and sister, Emma Jaco. He is survived by his daughter, Lidian Howard and husband Steve of Plano, Texas, sons; Bill Rogers of Estill Springs and Andy Rogers of Tullahoma. Grandchildren; Henry and Kate Howard and Chara Gault, Great Grandchildren; Wesley and Lily Gault, sisters; Audrey Cawthorn of Bradyville, TN., Ernestine Bryant of Woodbury, TN., Eilane Harris of Murfreesboro, TN., and very special caregiver, Ms. Rita Henderson of Estill Springs. A Private Funeral Service has been scheduled. It was Mr. Rogers\' wishes to be cremated afterwards. A Memorial Service will be announced and held at a later date for friends and family to attend and celebrate Jesse\'s life. Online condolences may be sent at www.GrantFuneralServices.net, as well as signing the guest book. Please contact Grant Funeral Services regarding additional information. In lieu of flowers the family requests donations be made in Mr. Rogers\' honor to the Shriner\'s Hospital for Children at ATTN: Office of Development, 2900 N. Rocky Point Drive, Tampa, FL 33607. worth of copper wire from a radiation zone at the Y-12 Nuclear Security Complex in Oak Ridge and sold it to a scrap metal business, triggering a radiation scare that forced the U.S. Department of Energy to call in a radiological detection team, according to court records reviewed by Knox News. A five-person radiological team was dispatched to the scrap metal business to conduct alpha/beta/gamma surveys, and found no evidence of contamination, according to a plea agreement filed in U.S. District Court. Assistant U.S. Attorney Trey Hamilton wrote in the plea agreements filed earlier this year the trio plotted to steal “partially-consumed spools of copper wire” that were being used in late 2018 as part of the DOE’s Nuclear Facilities Electrical Modernization project at Y-12. That project “includes replacing an early Cold War plant with a modern, more efficient and safer facility for conducting highly-enriched uranium operations,” Hamilton wrote. The work was taking place in “the protected area — an area of heightened security and safety precautions,” the plea agreement stated. “All material that passes through the protected area must be checked by appropriate personnel for radioactive contamination.” The contract laborers are identified in court records as Graham Cowan and John Michael Thomas, both electrical superintendents with Consolidated Nuclear Security, and Patrick Duggan, a Miller Electrical Co. electrician. Plot to profiteer Thomas and Cowan worked inside a radiation zone where the spools of copper wire were located, according to the plea agreements. The pair would essentially hide “partially-consumed” spools by moving them to another location within the protected area and later sneak them out of the radiation zone. Duggan, the records state, would then load the spools “on a trailer hitched to his truck” and haul them to his home “for subsequent delivery to a scrap-metal recycling company in exchange for money.” Hamilton says in court records the trio stole more than 4,000 pounds of copper wire and sold it for $9,000. They split the proceeds, according to court records. It’s not clear from the plea agreements when the thievery was discovered or how. Duggan told DOE investigators it was Thomas and Cowan who came up with the idea and lured him into the plot with a promise of cash. All three men are currently scheduled to enter guilty pleas in federal court April 24. Email Jamie Satterfield at jamie.satterfield@knoxnews.com and follow her on Twitter @jamiescoop. The Knoxville News Sentinel and The Oak Ridger are sister newspapers owned by Gannett.'}]

'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'Oneida, TNFull Forecast ❄️ Winter Storm Warning , Tennessee Sections Beyond The News The Nitty Gritty Mailing List Sign up to receive our daily emails! Connect RIGHT NOWOneida, TN » 60°F Current Events Severe Weather | SCSD Pay Raise | Guide to Government ❄️ Winter Storm Warning: 7 p.m. Sunday-7 a.m. Tuesday It started with a casual conversation between Children’s Center of the Cumberlands Executive Director Kellie Walker and a TN Dept. of Children’s Services investigator. And, within just days, an impressive charitable organization was born to help clothe Scott County’s abused and neglected children who are removed from their home. The name of the effort is Kip’s Kloset — named in memory of Kip McCoy Walker, Dustin and Kellie Walker’s newborn son who passed away on his birthday in May. Less than 10 weeks later, most would forgive Walker — who, along with her husband, owns The Beautique Tanning & Essentials in addition to serving as the Children’s Center’s executive director — if she were still mourning the tragic loss of her son. After all, it’s only been a couple of weeks since she returned to work after taking some time off to emotionally heal. “The week I went back was supposed to be the week that my maternity leave actually started,” Walker said recently. “Going back for me was hard because it was taking another step toward my new ‘normal.’ A life continued without a son that we had planned our lives around for the past year.” But Walker isn’t one to be still very long, even in a trying time. As Jonathan Orick of Engineered Fitness said last week, “If you’re blessed enough to know Kellie Walker, you know one of the kindest people in our community.” So, it probably should have been no surprise when Walker’s casual conversation with a DCS case worker about how to help the less fortunate children of Scott County quickly turned into an effort to put words into action. By July 30, Walker had made a Facebook post to appeal to her friends and neighbors to help. And the community responded in a big way. During that conversation that jump-started the effort, the DCS investigator mentioned that kids who are being taken into custody by the state need clothes — and there aren’t enough clothes to meet the need. “We see first-hand, babies come out of homes in only diapers and often times when kids are removed they have on filthy clothes, usually too small or too big, and they have limited clothes to take into their new home placement,” Walker said. Up until this point, the Children’s Center has given Walmart gift cards to DCS so that case workers can purchase kids new clothes or whatever they need when they’re removed from an abusive or neglectful home. But coronavirus has changed things. Walmart is no longer open 24 hours; the retail store closes at 10 p.m. each night. “When kids are removed in the middle of the night, they are at a loss,” Walker said. “She spoke about how nice it would be to just be able to grab stuff after they are showered at the center.” From there, Walker’s wheels began to turn. Before long, she’d come up with a plan to renovate a vacant office into a clothing closet to help meet the need. She enlisted her husband to help her, and a plan came together. “With COVID, we haven’t taken clothing donations that are used, so I knew it would have to be stocked with new items,” Walker said. “Plus, just being honest, I wanted the clothes to be new for the kids. Most have never had one article of clothing that was new with tags still on it and I felt like that in itself would be a gift and something special for them.” But there’s another issue that threatened to compound things: due to the coronavirus pandemic, the Children’s Center’s fundraising efforts and donations have been down significantly. The child advocacy center’s most visible fundraiser, the annual Nancy Swain Watters Memorial Walk in the spring, was canceled due to the pandemic. “I had no clue how I was going to stock this closet,” Walker said. “But I knew if we built it, the donations would come.” That’s where her husband, Dustin, came in. And on the way home from picking up building materials for the renovation project, the Walkers came up with an idea: a giveaway, where every person who donates clothing is entered into a drawing for a prize. Walker made the plea for prizes, and within just minutes, “I had so many friends with businesses in our community who had donated to the gift basket to give away,” she said. “So much so that we have enough now for more than one awesome giveaway.” The donations began to come in as soon as Walker made a post on her Facebook page. And then it just kept getting better. During their weekly Facebook Live episode Saturday evening, sisters Gabby and Milly Hill of Soul Sisters mentioned the Children’s Center closet and encouraged those who could give to do so. They also urged those who wanted to donate but didn’t want to shop to give a monetary donation that would help fill the gaps. They started the effort by donating a $100 gift card of their own for the prize drawing. “Long story short, at the end of that live show where she was on there to sell her shop’s items, they had over $7,000 that people had committed to help us fill the closet with clothes and to help us keep it stocked,” Walker said. The Hill sisters will invoice their customers for their donation when they invoice them for items that were purchased from Soul Sisters. “It was truly an emotional thing to be a part of, and God’s grace was shining bright through that Live show,” Walker said. It was also during that Soul Sisters Facebook Live show that Walker announced the clothes closet would be named in memory of her son. This is the challenge: before August 17, donate an article of clothing that is new with tags and your name will be entered to win a gift. For every article of clothing that is donated, your name goes in the pot another time. The more clothes you buy, the better chance you have of winning a gift basket. Sizes 0-3 months all the way through XXL adult are needed — both boys and girls clothes, along with pajamas, socks and underwear. Those who donate will have a chance to win a $300 gift card to Wilderness of the Smokies, a $100 gift card to The Skin Care Clinic, a $50 gift card from Scott County Florest, a large pizza from Baby J’s Pizza, a 4-pack of passes and more from Brimstone Recreation, a $50 Visa gift card from STAND, two months free tanning and a lotion from The Beautique, a $50 gift card from Angel Blessings Boutique, a $100 off coupon to Arch Angels Microblading, a $100 gift card from Soul Sisters, a $30 gift certificate from RaeZack’s, a $25 gift certificate from Perfecting Beauty, a $100 gift certificate from Engineered Fitness, a $25 gift certificate from The Vinyl Boutique, a $50 Texas Roadhouse giftcard from Chitwood Mountain Farms, a $25 gift certificate from Mike’s Station, a $30 gift certificate from C&C Customized Vinyl, and a $30 gift certificate from Bee Clever Cookies. The drawing will take place on Monday, August 17. Walker said she was overwhelmed by the response. “So many people have showed up in such a huge way,” she said. It started with Trent Coffey, executive director of STAND. “I asked him for a donation of a gift card and he opened his wallet personally, as well as STAND’s,” she said. “Scott County Florist (James and Penny Paul) was the same way. I asked for an item, and they gave, but they also gave personally to help us keep it going. “I know we say it all the time, how great our community is, but I was awestruck, and I still am, on how when there is a need, in this case for children who are taken into custody with absolutely nothing, the community shows up,” Walker said. Popular Share post: It started with a casual conversation between Children’s Center of the Cumberlands Executive Director Kellie Walker and a TN Dept. of Children’s Services investigator. And, within just days, an impressive charitable organization was born to help clothe Scott County’s abused and neglected children who are removed from their home. The name of the effort is Kip’s Kloset — named in memory of Kip McCoy Walker, Dustin and Kellie Walker’s newborn son who passed away on his birthday in May. Less than 10 weeks later, most would forgive Walker — who, along with her husband, owns The Beautique Tanning & Essentials in addition to serving as the Children’s Center’s executive director — if she were still mourning'}]

High 82F. Winds WSW at 5 to 10 mph. Chance of rain 30%.. Generally fair. Low 63F. Winds light and variable. Updated: June 2, 2024 @ 2:25 am Two years ago, Holladay Properties began renovations that have transformed The Factory at Franklin into a popular destination for shopping, dining and entertainment, with a vision to one day install a historic carousel that would support local non-profit initiatives. Now, with the Carousel s… On May 28, the Brentwood city commission held its regular meeting a day later than usual due to the holiday weekend. Commissioners welcomed new police officers to the city and celebrated the opening of the city’s first mountain bike trails before voting on budget items and a resolution to po… FRANKLIN – Both Hudson Allain and Claire Stegall competed last week at the Spring Fling Class AAA track and field championships with a team-first mentality. The pair of track stars also came away with a pair of individual championships in helping lead their teams to podium finishes. MURFREESBORO – State champions in track and field and tennis highlight a special edition of the Tim Thompson Premier Performers list for the week ending May 26. For the Williamson County Schools students who were part of the class of 24 and who graduated last weekend, their high school careers got off to a rough start. COVID-19 had made an unprecedented impact on life as we know it, and by the time the 2020-21 school year had gotten underway, WCS st… More than 420 Franklin High School seniors graduated in front of a packed house at their football stadium on May 23. FRANKLIN – Both Hudson Allain and Claire Stegall competed last week at the Spring Fling Class AAA track and field championships with a team-first mentality. The pair of track stars also came away with a pair of individual championships in helping lead their teams to podium finishes. Two years ago, Holladay Properties began renovations that have transformed The Factory at Franklin into a popular destination for shopping, dining and entertainment, with a vision to one day install a historic carousel that would support local non-profit initiatives. Now, with the Carousel s… To the Editor: To the Editor: Staff Writer Larry Reid received a Purple Heart for injuries he received on Aug. 18, 1968, while serving in Vietnam. Recently, while creating a shadowbox to showcase some of his military memorabilia, including his Purple Heart, Reid discovered that the certificate that was presented along with the medal and awarding orders was missing. Reid took a long, hard walk through his life in an effort to remember the last time he saw it. And then the light went on. He thinks it was 1988. “I was living at 1351 Columbia Ave. in Franklin,” he said. “I was going through a divorce. I had PTSD issues. That move was brutal, and I didn’t check to see if I had everything.” Reid, who was attached to the 9th Infantry, recalled that hot July day when he packed his belongings into a 1987 Thunderbird and left his wife, his children and Franklin. Years later, after finally getting the help he needed, Reid came to terms with the memories that haunted him and was able to settle his life. When he retired in 2011 to help his wife after a brain aneurism began a slow debilitating process for her, he decided to create the shadowbox. That was when he discovered the certificate was missing. Reid put on his thinking cap and tried to remember the last time he saw the certificate. “I thought it might be in the basement (of the Columbia Avenue house).” As he remembered, in 1988 it wasn’t a full basement. Half the area was concrete and the rest was a “root cellar type floor.” According to Reid, the certificate would have been in a box on a table or desk in the basement. “I think there were some kind of restaurant tables or a desk belonging to the property,” he added. “I can’t remember an attic.” Although Reid can apply to the Army to get a new certificate, he said that having the original would be wonderful. “The one I had was signed by Maj. Gen. Julian J. Ewell (now deceased),” he said. “He was our commanding officer. His great-grandfather was a cavalry officer in the Civil War.” For Reid, a Nashville native, that information created a connection between the commanding officer and the soldier. After Reid graduated from Overton High School, he was “having fun” as a musician with a Christian rock band in Nashville and making custom guitars with a friend. The fun ended when he was drafted at the age of 20. Reid did his basic training at Fort Campbell and was sent to Fort Lewis in Washington for advanced infantry training. “I just wanted to do good and go home,” he said. His next assignment was Vietnam, with Company E, 4/47th Battalion, 2nd Brigade, 9th Infantry Division. At the time, the 9th Infantry served with the Navy’s Mobile Riverine Force, known as the Brown Water Navy. The name is derived from its area of operation, the rivers and canals of the Mekong Delta. “I landed in Vietnam on April 3, 1968, the day before Martin Luther King (Jr.) was murdered,” he said. “I saw Kenny (a friend) crying and I wanted to know more about this Dr. King. I learned there was more to him than what I’d been told.” Reid, like so many soldiers at the time, was brought in to replace soldiers injured or killed during the first phase of the Tet Offensive, which began on Jan. 30, 1968. While awaiting orders, Reid met Jim Fous, an Army Ranger. “I thought since he was a Ranger, I should stick with him,” Reid said. The first night they went out on patrol together, Fous was killed. Within a couple weeks, Reid had become the platoon radio telephone operator, the guy who called in artillery and air strikes. “While we were walking (on a patrol), I heard about an air strike,” Reid said. Before an air strike, the target is marked by yellow smoke. Suddenly the platoon was surrounded by smoke. It was in the target area. “We ran just when the bombs started coming down,” he said. Reid said that the skirmishes and battles they encountered took their toll. “By August, we (3rd platoon) had 12 of the 26 we started with,” Reid said. “We called ourselves ‘The Dirty Dozen.’” On Aug. 18, 1968, Reid and his fellow soldiers were on an armored troop carrier landing craft heading down the Hai Muoi canal and preparing to go ashore to perform sweeps at designated areas. They were on the boat when they “were hit hard.” Reid was injured by shrapnel after coming under artillery fire. “I was hit by small pieces of hot lead and probably pieces of the boat I was in,” he said. “I still have some beaded metal under my skin.” Although he doesn’t remember much of that day, Reid said that at the time, he “pretty much came to grips with the fact I’m not going home,” and took care of others on the boat. By the end of the day, only four soldiers in the 3rd platoon were still fighting. Reid was one of them. “Only a couple of us were killed, but most were wounded badly and chopped out,” he said. The first medivac was shot down. I remember seeing that.” Reid was patched up and what was left of the 3rd platoon was attached to the 2nd platoon to finish the mission. The story is one of many chronicled in “Muddy Jungle Rivers,” a book written by Wendall Affield, the sailor driving the carrier. In October 1968, a staff officer asked Reid if he could type. “I took typing at Overton High School — the only boy — because all the girls were taking typing,” Reid said. That class got him sent to the tactical operations center in Ben Tre for the remainder of his tour of duty. “I don’t have an explanation for how I survived,” Reid said. “I had plenty of opportunities to come home in a box.” Staff Writer Log In Keep it Clean.
